te to vineyards wherever it landed. He tells how scientists, viticulturalists, researchers, and others came together to save the world’s vineyards and, with years of observation and research, developed a strategy of resistance. Among other topics, the book discusses phylloxera as an important case study of how one invasive species can colonize new habitats and examines California’s past and present problems with it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGrapesxDiseases and pestsxHistoryy19th century. 0aGrapesxDiseases and pestsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhylloxera. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  abiological and economic disaster.  abook about phylloxera.  adeveloped strategy of resistance.  aeighteen sixties.  ainvaded south of france.  ainvasive species colonize new habitats.  ajourneyed across oceans.  alays waste to vineyards.  aresearchers.  ascientific warfare against phylloxera.  ascientists.  aspread throughout europe.  aviticulturalists.  awine industry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026548640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094885340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948853423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520948853/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY